        <h3>2. Injuries</h3>


   <p>You need to be up to date if someone gets injured in the league. This usually creates opportunity for other players that could be worth picking up. Ask yourself who is going to be the main beneficiary of the playing time when that player is out. Did that player do well while the injured player was out in the past? Having a quality pickup after an injury can be a season changer for your team.</p>

   <p>You also want to look at all of the injured players to see if a quality player is about to start playing again. Someone could have dropped a stud that has been injured for 2 months but is about to come back. There could be someone in your league that people are forgetting about.</p>
    
     
   <h3>3. Daily Leaders</h3>

     <p>Another good tip to pick up players on the waiver wire is to look at the daily leaderboards while games are in progress. If you see someone that has 17 fantasy points in the first quarter and has been doing well recently, chances are, you should pick that player up. If you look at the daily leaderboards you could see something before others do to give you a leg up on the competition. </p>

      <img src="http://i.imgur.com/6Km23CU.png" class="img-rounded" style="width:350px; height:280px;" />

      <h3>4. Minutes</h3>

     <p>You should also pay very close attention to the minutes the a player puts in each night. Check to see if their minutes has a positive trend, or incresing over time. This is a great thing to look out for if you are looking to grab a steal off the waiver wires. </p>

